Preheat the #oven{} to 200°C. Slice the @Ciabatta{2} in half and lay them cut side up on a large #baking tray{} in a single layer. Peel and grate the @Garlic Clove{2} (or use a #garlic press{}) and pop in a small #bowl{} with the @Olive Oil{2%tbsp}, mix well. Drizzle the garlic oil over the cut side of the bread. Season with @salt{} and set aside for later.

Halve the @Baby Plum Tomatoes{125}. Slice lengthways into the @Avocado{1}. Once you reach the stone turn the avocado around to cut it in half. Twist each half and pull it apart. Remove the stone then scoop out the flesh onto a #cutting board{} and chop into 2cm chunks. Trim the @Spring Onion{2} then slice thinly.

Halve, peel and slice the @Red Onion{1} as thinly as you can. Heat a drizzle of @Olive Oil for the Dressing{1%tbsp} in a #frying pan{} on medium high heat. Add the red onion to the pan and fry, stirring frequently until softened ~{6-8%minutes}. Add the @Sugar{1%tbsp}, @Water{2%tbsp}, and half the @Balsamic Vinegar{6%tbsp}, reduce the heat and simmer, stirring occasionally, ~{2-3%minutes}, until caramelised. Transfer the onions to a bowl. Wipe out your frying pan.

Return the frying pan to the heat over high heat. Add the @Serrano Ham{4%slices} and cook until golden and crispy, ~{1-2%minutes} each side. Transfer to a #plate{} lined with #kitchen roll{} and set aside.

> You may need to cook the serrano ham slices in batches if your pan is small - you want to cook them in a single layer so they get crispy.

Meanwhile, bake the ciabatta on the top shelf of the oven until golden and crispy, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Mix together the olive oil and remaining balsamic vinegar in a large bowl. Season with salt and @pepper{} and mix together. Pop the tomatoes, avocado and spring onion into the bowl with the dressing. Add the @Wild Rocket{40} and toss to coat everything evenly.

Place two ciabatta per person onto your plates. Divide the caramelized onion among the ciabatta halves. Top each half with a handful of the salad mixture. Drain the @Mozzarella{1} and tear it into small pieces and place on top of the salad. Crumble the serrano ham into shards and arrange them on top. Enjoy!

> If you've doubled up on serrano ham, cook the extra ham in the same way, but you may need to cook the serrano ham slices in batches if your pan is small - you want to cook them in a single layer so they get crispy.